                        Magazine article
                    
Journal of Commercial Lending

Developing Rational Policies for Letters of Credit 
By Harton, H. Lynn

Read preview








                            Magazine article
                        
Journal of Commercial Lending

Developing Rational Policies for Letters of Credit 
By Harton, H. Lynn

Read preview




Article excerpt

  Letters of credit (L/Cs) have been an integral part of commercial business transactions for hundreds of years. Yet, owing to their detailed documentation requirements, L/Cs have typically been handled by specialists in the banking industry, leaving account officers somewhat in the dark regarding the mystery of L/Cs.    In reality, account officers are the best people to prospect for L/C opportunities and to manage the risk in existing and prospective L/C transactions. By developing and communicating rational policies concerning the use of L/Cs, banks can help account officers be more effective with this important bank product line.    A letter of credit (L/C) involves at least three parties: a bank (the issuing bank), a customer on whose behalf the L/C is issued (the applicant), and a person to whom payment from the L/C will flow (the beneficiary). L/Cs are written instruments issued by banks stating that payments will be made on behalf of applicants to beneficiaries, provided that the beneficiary fulfills all the conditions described in the instrument. In essence, the effect of an L/C is to substitute the credit of a bank, which is generally well known, for the credit of an applicant, which is either not as well known or not considered to be adequate by the beneficiary.    In issuing the L/C, the bank becomes entitled to reimbursement from the applicant for any payments that the bank properly makes. The applicant may provide collateral to the bank to secure the repayment of the reimbursement obligation, or the bank may simply rely on the applicant's promise to pay. The bank receives fees for issuing and handling L/Cs.       Principle of Independence    As professionals, bankers have a duty to protect not only the interest of their banks but also their customers' interests. Applicants are often unaware of the risk undertaken when they apply for an L/C.    Applicants must be made aware that the relationship between an issuing bank and the beneficiary is an entirely separate contractual relationship, unlike that between the applicant and the beneficiary. The bank deals in documents only (not merchandise or performance), and it therefore cannot ensure that the underlying transaction has been fulfilled to the satisfaction of the applicant. When all stipulated documents are presented, the issuing bank must pay the beneficiary.    The applicant must not rely on the L/C for protection from the beneficiary's performance problems. The bank's responsibility is only to examine documents with reasonable care and to ascertain that they appear to comply with the requirements of the L/C. Once the L/C is issued, the applicant faces the risk that the L/C may be paid through fraudulent actions of the beneficiary.    Another aspect of the independence of the relationships of the three parties involved relates to amendments of the L/C. Proposed amendments must be acceptable to all parties (issuer, applicant, and beneficiary) to be considered in effect. No party has the power to make unilateral changes in the terms of an irrevocable L/C.       Two Categories    L/Cs issued by my bank fall into two broad categories - commercial (trade-related) and standby.       Commercial L/Cs    Commercial, or trade-related, L/Cs are used to carry out specific trade transactions involving the sale or purchase of goods. Sellers of goods desire to know that if they perform according to the terms of their agreement with the purchaser (that is, deliver the product), they will be paid. The presence of the L/C from a financially strong third party gives the seller (beneficiary) that assurance. By providing this assurance to the beneficiary, the bank obviously assumes credit risk.    As previously mentioned, L/Cs rely on documents, not verified performance. For a beneficiary to claim payment under an L/C, the beneficiary's documents must conform exactly to those required by the L/C. … 






